# Next.js 16 for Absolute Beginners

# Part 6 — Data Fetching: Why Modern Next.js Doesn't Need `useEffect`

> **Goal of this lesson:** Learn how data fetching works in modern Next.js, why most `useEffect` data fetching is obsolete, and how to fetch data efficiently using React Server Components.

---

# The Old Way of Fetching Data

For many years, React developers wrote code like this:

```jsx
"use client";

import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export default function UsersPage() {
    const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
    const [loading, setLoading] =
        useState(true);

    useEffect(() => {
        async function loadUsers() {
            const response =
                await fetch(
                    "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users"
                );

            const data =
                await response.json();

            setUsers(data);
            setLoading(false);
        }

        loadUsers();
    }, []);

    if (loading) {
        return <p>Loading...</p>;
    }

    return (
        <div>
            {users.map(user => (
                <p key={user.id}>
                    {user.name}
                </p>
            ))}
        </div>
    );
}
```

This works.

But look at how much code we wrote:

* `useState`
* `useEffect`
* loading state
* async function
* state updates
* conditional rendering

And this is just for displaying some data.

---

# What Actually Happens?

Let's visualize what the browser is doing.

```text
User visits page
        ↓
Download JavaScript
        ↓
Execute React
        ↓
Render empty page
        ↓
Fetch API
        ↓
Wait
        ↓
Receive data
        ↓
Render again
```

There are multiple steps.

There are multiple renders.

There are multiple waits.

---

# React Server Components Change Everything

Suppose the server can fetch data.

Why do this?

```text
Server
   ↓
Send JS
   ↓
Browser
   ↓
Fetch Data
   ↓
Render
```

Instead, why not do this?

```text
Server
   ↓
Fetch Data
   ↓
Render UI
   ↓
Send Result
```

This is exactly what Next.js does.

---

# Your First Server Fetch

Create:

```text
app/users/page.tsx
```

Write:

```tsx
export default async function UsersPage() {

    const response =
        await fetch(
            "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users"
        );

    const users =
        await response.json();

    return (
        <main>

            <h1>
                Users
            </h1>

            {users.map(user => (
                <div key={user.id}>
                    {user.name}
                </div>
            ))}

        </main>
    );
}
```

---

# That's It?

Yes.

No:

```tsx
useState()
```

No:

```tsx
useEffect()
```

No:

```tsx
loading
```

No:

```tsx
setState()
```

Just:

```tsx
await fetch()
```

---

# Why Does This Work?

Because your component executes on the server.

```text
Browser
    |
Request Page
    |
    V
Next.js Server
    |
Fetch API
    |
Build HTML
    |
Send Result
    |
Browser Displays
```

The browser never performs the fetch.

---

# Understanding async Components

This may look strange:

```tsx
export default async function Page() {
}
```

In traditional React, this was impossible.

In Next.js Server Components, it's normal.

Example:

```tsx
export default async function Page() {

    const data =
        await getData();

    return (
        <div>
            {data.title}
        </div>
    );
}
```

Think of a Server Component as:

```text
HTML Template
        +
Database Query
        +
API Call
```

combined into one function.

